es of this type that may have contributed to the surname. (ii) locative name, occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Totehill</i> in 1251."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuthill","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of <b>Toothill</b>, primarily a Yorkshire habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (Yorkshire) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancashire), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwickshire), and Tothill (Lincolnshire). There are several further minor placenames of this type that may have contributed to the surname. Also occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Totta</i> (genitive <i>Tottan</i>) + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]},{"name":"Tootell","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tothill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tuttle","meanings":["English (Norfolk, Suffolk and Berkshire):","possibly a variant of <b>Thirkell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)irkill</i>, <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Norse <i>Thorkell</i>, <i>Thorkil</i>, <i>Thurkil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Thorketill</i> from the god's name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘kettle, cauldron’).","variant of   Tuthill  ."]},{"name":"Tutill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootal","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tott","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Tot(te)</i> (Old English  <i>Totta</i>,  <i>Tota</i>).  See also  Totty  ,   Tutt  , and compare Sabyna Tottedoghter’, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Kirkby Malham, WR Yorks); Radulphus Totusone, 1377 in   Poll Tax   (Frisby on the Wreak, Leics). Some early bearers may belong with (2) or (3).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>tot(te)</i> ‘simpleton, fool’.","3  English: locative name from Middle English  <i>tot(e)</i> ‘lookout hill’ (Old English  <i>tōt(e)</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or by a lookout hill, or toponymic, for someone from a place so named, such as Toat Farm in Pulborough (Sussex) and Toat Hill in Slinfold (Sussex).  Compare  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tottle","meanings":["1  English:  see  Toothill  .","2  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name * <i>Totel</i> (Old English  <i>Tottel</i>)."]},{"name":"Tootill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootle","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Tuthill  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":43,"year"